Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he is the third to put to the vote a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of the voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results that referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were null votes and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls at the exit of the polling stations and a count by a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to the "yes", estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The " Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly " , he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who lead the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, to be held in full calm, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, referred to a 444-point text consolidating the " new socialism " advocated by the President.
The draft Constitution implied an increase in the State ' s power over the economy, reserving for it the " development planning " of a country that lived essentially on the extraction of oil by foreign companies and on foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to serve up to two consecutive terms of four years each and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he would use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also strengthens the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally foresees the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 abductees have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after they were released Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good on arrival at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the Al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical testing, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages were taken by 35 unknown abductors while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since gone from one to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of the safari organization.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces members, carried aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled," said the official, who remained anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men in the secret services, in the special forces," he said.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
Earlier, the Sudanese army said it had intercepted an all-terrain vehicle during a patrol in which the kidnappers were on board, killing six of them, including the Chadian chief, and detaining two.
It also claimed that they were related to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
Letters - Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes the headlines and occupies the current electoral campaign.
Better this way.
But a part of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that starve to death?
Which politician will dare remind the federal government to neglect its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don’t we have true laws that effectively preserve our heritage as in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government spends three and a half million euros to restore only the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and all of this in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Quebec History Societies, at least 40,000 benevolent people regrouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving with little money piles of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
It is these who are often the guardian dogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and desperation when promoters and officials throw their bulldozers at our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The governments of the Netherlands nationalize a part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands states - being the first in Europe - will help with a nationalization to the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis which is in trouble due to the effect of the mortgage crisis of the North American market: the three countries will support in total with 11.2 billion euros to this financial and insurance institution that also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the President of the European Central Bank and the head of economic competition of the European Commission.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the Eurozone crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves more than a year ago, therefore the decisions taken with respect to the Bank, in a certain sense can be considered as precedents.
According to the decision taken early on Sunday, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank is sure to sell a portion of its business, including most of the activities – mainly insurance – purchased last year from Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis shares began a sharp decline last week and for the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, this bank is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The company’s shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Looking at current stock prices, the total value of the group’s capital in the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management blamed the sharp fall in Fortis shares on the insecurities of the US market in relation to the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday, stocks showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank’s new managing director.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured that investors had nothing to worry about, they would not lose their money.
Among the Bank’s clients so far there has been no panic, they did not invade the bank offices to withdraw their money.
The Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
In the U.S., life and health insurance companies when viewing drug purchase data, often deny signing an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of the data of the recipes in all cases joins the approval of the given person.
The same must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we entrust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the program tracking prescriptions.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and the amount of compensation dependent on the client’s health status and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply don’t make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him already knowing the result of the control.
Ten years ago Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: with the customer identification number easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the customer.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a number of risk, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has hardly anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some drugs are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former do not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, request the patient's approval.
Authorities are already forcing them to do so, though they have not been fined for negligence so far.
Some companies recently also compile the results of laboratory tests and by linking them with drug consumption data get more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is becoming more and more difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the right to the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: hence he developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the individual for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, in spite of everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
Global menu of Marseille
EU doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocally trading partners, this topic in addition to the other mostly global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, focusing mainly on cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs but member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been dealt with at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, Commission President, and Javier Solana, India’s top foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, India’s prime minister, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase their trade to more than one hundred billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
They have thus legally harmonized the 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi ranks only ninth among the EU’s trading partners.
The summit paid attention to global issues.
Both sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of the latter - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also pressed, although both sides bear great responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate agenda, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20%.
India also agrees with this, just as next year’s climate conference should reach a global agreement and cut through 2050 by fifty percent the production of greenhouse gases.
They also wished to hamper the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports, the deal would be for a period of 15 years.
