Steve Fossett's plane found missing a year ago
The wreckage of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris has been found on an altiplano at 3,000 meters above sea level, in the area of the Mammoth Lakes Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Wood County Commissioner John Anderson has dispelled the doubts that remained: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is proper to what Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance," he said in a press conference.
No human remains were found either on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire was presumed dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Office (NTSB) has announced that a few hours after the sighting of the wreckage, a squadron of researchers has been sent to identify the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal remains of Fossett have been found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two Fossett-named documents, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
The search for Fossett had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, by the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the world tour in a hot air balloon: two lonely weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the round of the world by plane and without stops.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don’t expect
An off-scheme SUV with an original and well-established design with defined lines and definite angles.
It is this, in summary, Glk the last born among the "compact" all-terrain vans of the house of the star with which Mercedes-Benz has sought to give a window of novelty in this sector.
The communication that will accompany the launch of the Glk SUV, available in the Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17th, will be unexpected and unconventional.
The advertising campaign that accompanied the debut of the new car will launch an unprecedented mode of communication through a 3D advertising campaign, used for the first time in Italy by a car brand.
A project with maxi-posters, articulated in three different phases, that will dominate the central street of the Milanese shopping, avenue Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic version and thanks to special glasses distributed on the Avenida Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, looking at the images you will have the impression that the car comes out of the poster.
Successively, through the use of the innovative technology Elumina8 the new Glk will be illuminated at different times in all its details, to be recomposed in a single image.
Undoubtedly Mercedes with this advertising is trying to introduce something new in the stereotype of automotive communication.
Can this formula capture the interest of future buyers? we will see.
